This copy does not work as well as the others.  Once an episode plays, it does not automatically move to the next episode, if you are not paying attention, you will push play on the same episode that had just completed.  This season is done almost as if some one taped if off the TV and tried to put it in shape.  I kept it because I had waited a long time for the Nash Bridges series.  After the first three seasons, everything stopped.  then you came out with the entire six seasons, which I wouldn't buy because I had the earlier copies.  it is as if two different companies released the first half as opposed the second half.

Just finished watching this season of Nash, and think it might be the best one yet.  There is lots of action and humor, and of course Nash (pretty much like Don Johnson himself) is just too damn charming, you can't help but like him even though he goes from one woman to another without much of a break in between ... he clearly loves women of all ages, and they are all happy to indulge him.  Aside from all of that, there is really solid acting, a true depth to the relationships between the main characters.  I think the best acting in this season is from Jaime P. Gomez, as Evan who reaches rock bottom and climbs his way back to a meaningful life, and from Jeff Perry, as Harvey, in one of the final scenes, cleaning out Evan's desk.  There are no words, just raw emotion that left me with a lump in my throat.  Great show, wish Evan's character had not been written out, and wish there were more than one more season to look forward to.  And ... maybe I mentioned this in a previous review, but I think Nash is a pre-cursor to Gibbs of NCIS .... from the clothes, the rules, the complicated private life ....

We love the whole Nash thing, but this season is special.  The descent of Evan and the way he was able to find to return is something you don't see very often.  There was some depth to this season that made it stand out.  They way these issues were handled by the show was singular.  I don't remember any other show dealing with this theme this clearly.
